AU  - Wu, Tong
AU  - Guo, Jing
TI  - Multiobjective Design of 2-D-Material-Based Field-Effect Transistors with Machine Learning Methods
LA  - eng
JF  - Ieee Transactions on Electron Devices
VL  - 68
IS  - 11
SP  - 5476
EP  - 5482
PY  - 2021
SN  - 15579646, 00189383
PB  - Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers Inc.
DO  - 10.1109/TED.2021.3085701
AB  - Design optimization of emerging nanoscale transistor technologies often requires careful design tradeoff between many objectives, including speed, power, variability, and so on. By leveraging machine learning (ML) methods, we develop a multiobjective optimization (MOO) framework for 2-D-material-based field-effect transistors (FETs) near the scaling limit. The MOO design framework performs gradient-free efficient global optimization and offers the option of using active learning. Optimum designs with a tradeoff between transistor speed, power, and variability are identified automatically for transition metal dichalcogenide (TMDC) and black phosphorene FETs by applying the MOO design framework that couples ML methods to quantum transport device simulations. The design optimization results show that the International Roadmap of Devices and Systems (IRDS) target of 2025 and 2028 technology nodes can be met by 2-D FETs.
ER  -

